In [10]:
# Filling missing values

train_df['Gender'].fillna(train_df['Gender'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
train_df['Married'].fillna(train_df['Married'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
train_df['Dependents'].fillna(train_df['Dependents'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
train_df['Self_Employed'].fillna(train_df['Self_Employed'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
train_df['LoanAmount'].fillna(train_df['LoanAmount'].mean(), inplace=True)
train_df['Loan_Amount_Term'].fillna(train_df['Loan_Amount_Term'].mean(), inplace=True)
train_df['Credit_History'].fillna(train_df['Credit_History'].mean(), inplace=True)

# Set a smaller figure size for better visualization
small_figsize = (5, 3)

# List of categorical columns to be plotted
columns_to_plot = ['Gender', 'Married', 'Dependents', 'Education', 'Self_Employed', 'Property_Area', 'Loan_Status']

# Loop through each column and create count plots
# Create count plot for the current column with smaller size

for column in columns_to_plot:
    plt.figure(figsize=small_figsize)
    sns.countplot(x=column, data=train_df)
    plt.title(f'{column} Counts')
    plt.show()

    # Calculate and print counts for the current column
    column_counts = train_df[column].value_counts()
    
    # Print column name along with counts
    print(f"\nNumber of {column}s:")
    print(column_counts.to_string())
    print('\n' + '='*30 + '\n')

# Use SelectKBest to select top features
selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k='all')
X_selected = selector.fit_transform(X, y)

# Get feature scores and names
feature_scores = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': X.columns, 'Score': selector.scores_})
feature_scores = feature_scores.sort_values(by='Score', ascending=False)

# Select top features based on scores
top_features = feature_scores['Feature'].head(5).tolist()
print("Top Features:", top_features)

In [29]:
def classify(model, x, y):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Accuracy is", model.score(X_test, y_test) * 100)
    score = cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=5)
    print("Cross-validation accuracy is", score.mean() * 100)

# Assuming X and y are defined before this point
model = LogisticRegression()
classify(model, X, y)

lr_model = LogisticRegression()
lr_params = {
    'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2']
}
lr_grid = GridSearchCV(lr_model, lr_params, cv=5)
lr_grid.fit(X, y)
#print("\nBest parameters for Logistic Regression:", lr_grid.best_params_)
print("Best cross-validation accuracy:", lr_grid.best_score_ * 100)

    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Accuracy is", model.score(X_test, y_test) * 100)
    score = cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=5)
    print("Cross-validation accuracy is", np.mean(score) * 100)

def classify(model, x, y):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    print("Accuracy is", model.score(X_test, y_test) * 100)
    score = cross_val_score(model, x, y, cv=5)
    print("Cross-validation accuracy is", np.mean(score) * 100)

# Load the test dataset
test_df = pd.read_csv(r'C:\Users\Abhishek\predictions.csv')

# Load the predictions dataset
predictions_df = pd.read_csv(r'C:\Users\Abhishek\predictions.csv')

# Merge DataFrames based on their index (assuming 'Actual' and 'Predicted' are columns)
combined_df = pd.merge(test_df, predictions_df, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# Save the combined dataset to a new CSV file
combined_df.to_csv(r'C:\Users\Abhishek\combined_dataset.csv', index=False)
